#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:-1
msgid ""
"This is a guide for people who review package pull requests and includes "
"criteria for them to be merged into the develop branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:12
msgid "Package Review Guide"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:14
msgid ""
"Package reviews are performed with the goals of minimizing build errors and "
"making packages as **uniform and stable** as possible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:16
msgid ""
"This section establishes guidelines to help assess Spack community `package "
"repository <https://github.com/spack/spack-packages>`_ pull requests (PRs). "
"It describes the considerations and actions to be taken when reviewing new "
"and updated `Spack packages <https://spack.readthedocs.io/en/latest/"
"packaging_guide_creation.html#structure-of-a-package>`_. In some cases, "
"there are possible solutions to common issues."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:21
msgid "How to use this guide"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:23
msgid ""
"Whether you are a :ref:`Package Reviewer <package-reviewers>`, :ref:"
"`Maintainer <package-maintainers>`, or :ref:`Committer <committers>`, this "
"guide highlights relevant aspects to consider when reviewing package pull "
"requests. If you are a :ref:`Package Contributor <package-contributors>` (or "
"simply ``Contributor``), you may also find the information and solutions "
"useful in your work. While we provide information on what to look for, the "
"changes themselves should drive the actual review process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:29
msgid ""
":ref:`Confirmation of successful package builds <build_success_reviews>` of "
"**all** affected versions can reduce the amount of effort needed to review a "
"PR. However, packaging conventions and the combinatorial nature of versions "
"and directives mean each change should still be checked."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:33
msgid "Reviewing a new package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:35
msgid ""
"If the pull request includes a new package, then focus on answering the "
"following questions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:37
msgid ""
"Should the :ref:`package <suitable_package>` be added to the repository?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:38
msgid ""
"Does the package :ref:`structure <structure_reviews>` conform to conventions?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:39
msgid "Are the directives and their options correct?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:40 ../../../package_review_guide.rst:55
msgid ""
"Do all :ref:`automated checks <automated_checks_reviews>` pass? If not, are "
"there easy-to-resolve CI and/or test issues that can be addressed or does "
"the submitter need to investigate the failures?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:42
msgid ""
"Is there :ref:`confirmation <build_success_reviews>` that every version "
"builds successfully on at least one platform?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:44 ../../../package_review_guide.rst:59
msgid "Refer to the relevant sections below for more guidance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:47
msgid "Reviewing changes to an existing package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:49
msgid ""
"If the pull request includes changes to an existing package, then focus on "
"answering the following questions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:51
msgid ""
"Are there any changes to the package :ref:`structure <structure_reviews>` "
"and, if so, do they conform to conventions?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:52
msgid ""
"If there are new or updated directives, then are they and their options "
"correct?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:53
msgid ""
"If there are changes to the :ref:`url or its equivalent "
"<url_equivalent_reviews>`, are the older versions still correct?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:54
msgid ""
"If there are changes to the :ref:`git or equivalent URL <vcs_url_reviews>`, "
"do older branches exist in the new location?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:57
msgid ""
"Is there :ref:`confirmation <build_success_reviews>` that every new version "
"builds successfully on at least one platform?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:64
msgid "Package suitability"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:66
msgid ""
"It is rare that a package would be considered inappropriate for inclusion in "
"the public `Spack package <https://github.com/spack/spack-packages>`_ "
"repository. One exception is making packages for standard Perl modules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:69
msgid ""
"**Action.** Should you find the software is not appropriate, ask that the "
"package be removed from the PR if it is one of multiple affected files or "
"suggest the PR be closed. In either case, explain the reason for the request."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:74
msgid "CORE Perl modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:76
msgid ""
"In general, modules that are part of the standard installation for all "
"listed Perl versions (i.e., ``CORE``) should **not be implemented or "
"contributed**. Details on the exceptions and process for checking Perl "
"modules can be found in the :ref:`Perl build system <suitable_perl_modules>` "
"documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:82
msgid "Package structure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:84
msgid ""
"The `convention <https://spack.readthedocs.io/en/latest/"
"packaging_guide_creation.html#structure-of-a-package>`_ for structuring "
"Spack packages has metadata (key properties) listed first followed by "
"directives then methods:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:86
msgid ":ref:`url_equivalent_reviews`;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:87
msgid ":ref:`vcs_url_reviews`;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:88
msgid ":ref:`maintainers_reviews`;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:89
msgid ":ref:`license_reviews`;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:90
msgid ":ref:`version_reviews`;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:91
msgid ":ref:`variant_reviews`;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:92
msgid ":ref:`depends_on_reviews`;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:93
msgid ""
":ref:`packaging_conflicts` and :ref:`packaging_requires` directives; then"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:94
msgid "methods."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:96
msgid ""
"`Groupings <https://spack.readthedocs.io/en/latest/packaging_guide_creation."
"html#grouping-directives>`_ using ``with`` context managers can affect the "
"order of dependency, conflict, and requires directives to some degree. "
"However, they do cut down on visual clutter and make packages more readable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:99
msgid ""
"**Action.** If you see clear deviations from the convention, request that "
"they be addressed. When in doubt, ask others with merge privileges for "
"advice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:106
msgid "``url``, ``url_for_version``, or URL equivalent"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:108
msgid ""
"Changes to URLs may invalidate existing versions, which should be checked "
"when there is a URL-related modification. All packages have a URL, though "
"for some :ref:`build-systems` it is derived automatically and not visible in "
"the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:111
msgid ""
"Reasons :ref:`versions <versions-and-fetching>` may become invalid include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:113
msgid "the new URL does not support Spack version extrapolation;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:114
msgid ""
"the addition of or changes to ``url_for_version`` involve checks of the "
"``spec``'s version instead of the ``version`` argument or the (usually "
"older) versions are not covered;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:115
msgid ""
"extrapolation of the derived URL no longer matches that of older versions; "
"and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:116
msgid "the older versions are no longer available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:118
msgid ""
"**Action.** Checking existing version directives with checksums can usually "
"be done manually with the modified package using `spack checksum <https://"
"spack.readthedocs.io/en/latest/command_index.html#spack-checksum>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:121
msgid ""
"**Solutions.** Options for resolving the problem that can be suggested for "
"investigation depend on the source."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:124
msgid ""
"In simpler cases involving ``url`` or ``url_for_version``, invalid versions "
"can sometimes be corrected by ensuring all versions are covered by "
"``url_for_version``. Alternatively, especially for older versions, the "
"version-specific URL can be added as an argument to the ``version`` "
"directive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:127
msgid ""
"Sometimes the derived URLs of versions on the hosting system can vary. This "
"commonly happens with Python packages. For example, the case of one or more "
"letters in the package name may change at some point (e.g., `py-sphinx "
"<https://github.com/spack/spack-packages/blob/develop/repos/spack_repo/"
"builtin/packages/py_sphinx/package.py>`_). Also, dashes may be replaced with "
"underscores (e.g., `py-scikit-build <https://github.com/spack/spack-packages/"
"blob/develop/repos/spack_repo/builtin/packages/py_scikit_build/package."
"py>`_). In some cases, both changes can occur for the same package. As these "
"examples illustrate, it is sometimes possible to add a ``url_for_version`` "
"method to override the default derived URL to ensure the correct one is "
"returned."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:134
msgid ""
"If older versions are no longer available and there is a chance someone has "
"the package in a build cache, the usual approach is to first suggest :ref:"
"`deprecating <deprecate>` them in the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:139
msgid "``git``, ``hg``, ``svn``, or ``cvs``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:141
msgid ""
"If the :ref:`repository-specific URL <vcs-fetch>` for fetching branches or "
"the version control system (VCS) equivalent changes, there is a risk that "
"the listed versions are no longer accessible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:143
msgid ""
"**Action.** You may need to check the new source repository to confirm the "
"presence of all of the listed versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:149
msgid "``maintainers`` directive"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:151
msgid ""
"**Action.** If the new package does not have a :ref:`maintainers "
"<maintainers>` directive, ask the Contributor to add one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:156 ../../../package_review_guide.rst:170
msgid "This request is optional for existing packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:158 ../../../package_review_guide.rst:172
msgid "Be prepared for them to refuse."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:163
msgid "``license`` directive"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:165
msgid ""
"**Action.** If the new package does not have a :ref:`license "
"<package_license>` directive, ask the Contributor to investigate and add it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:177
msgid "``version`` directives"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:179
msgid ""
"In general, Spack packages are expected to be built from source code. There "
"are a few exceptions (e.g., :ref:`BundlePackage <bundlepackage>`). Typically "
"every package will have at least one :ref:`version <versions-and-fetching>` "
"directive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:183
msgid ""
"The goals of reviewing version directives are to confirm that versions are "
"listed in the proper order **and** that the arguments for new and updated "
"versions are correct."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:187
msgid ""
"Additions and removals of version directives should generally trigger a "
"review of :ref:`dependencies <depends_on_reviews>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:190
msgid "``version`` directive order"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:192
msgid ""
"By :ref:`convention <versions-and-fetching>` version directives should be "
"listed in descending order, from newest to oldest. If branch versions are "
"included, then they should be listed first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:195
msgid ""
"**Action.** When versions are being added, check the ordering of the "
"directives. Request that the directives be  re-ordered if any of the "
"directives do not conform to the convention."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:201
msgid ""
"Edge cases, such as manually downloaded software, may be difficult to "
"confirm."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:204
msgid "Checksums, commits, tags, and branches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:206
msgid "**Checksums, commits, and tags**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:207
msgid ""
"Normally these version arguments are automatically validated by GitHub "
"Actions using `spack ci verify-versions <https://spack.readthedocs.io/en/"
"latest/command_index.html#spack-ci-verify-versions>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:209
msgid ""
"**Action.** Review the PR's ``verify-checksums`` precheck to confirm. If "
"necessary, checksums can usually be manually confirmed using `spack checksum "
"<https://spack.readthedocs.io/en/latest/command_index.html#spack-checksum>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:215
msgid ""
"From a security and reproducibility standpoint, it is important that Spack "
"be able to verify downloaded source. This is accomplished using a hash (e."
"g., checksum or commit). See :ref:`checksum verification <checksum-"
"verification>` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:219
msgid ""
"Exceptions are allowed in rare cases, such as software supplied from "
"reputable vendors. When in doubt, ask others with merge privileges for "
"advice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:222
msgid "**Tags**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:223
msgid ""
"If a ``tag`` is provided without a ``commit``, the downloaded software will "
"not be trusted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:225
msgid ""
"**Action.** Suggest that the ``commit`` argument be included in the "
"``version`` directive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:228
msgid "**Branches**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:229
msgid ""
"Confirming new branch versions involves checking that the branches exist in "
"the repository *and* that the version and branch names are consistent. Let's "
"take each in turn."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:232
msgid ""
"**Action.** Confirming branch existence often involves checking the source "
"repository though is not necessary if there is confirmation that the branch "
"was built successfully from the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:235
msgid ""
"In general, the version and branch names should match. When they do not, it "
"is sometimes the result of people not being aware of how Spack handles :ref:"
"`version-comparison`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:238
msgid ""
"**Action.** If there is a name mismatch, especially for the most common "
"branch names (e.g., ``develop``, ``main``, and ``master``), ask why and "
"suggest the arguments be changed such that they match the actual branch name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:241
msgid "**Manual downloads**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:243
msgid ""
"**Action.** Since these can be difficult to confirm, it is acceptable to "
"rely on the package's Maintainers, if any."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:247
msgid "Deprecating versions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:249
msgid ""
"If someone is deprecating versions, it is good to find out why. Sometimes "
"there are concerns, such as security or lack of availability."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:252
msgid ""
"**Action.** Suggest the Contributor review the :ref:`deprecation guidelines "
"<deprecate>` before finalizing the changes if they haven't already explained "
"why they made the choice in the PR description or comments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:258
msgid "``variant`` directives"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:260
msgid ""
":ref:`Variants <variants>` represent build options so any changes involving "
"these directives should be reflected elsewhere in the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:263
msgid "Adding or modifying variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:265
msgid ""
"**Action.** Confirm that new or modified variants are actually used in the "
"package. The most common uses are additions and changes to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:269
msgid ":ref:`dependencies <depends_on_reviews>`;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:270
msgid "configure options; and/or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:271
msgid "build arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:274
msgid "Removing or disabling variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:276
msgid ""
"If the variant is still relevant to listed version directives, it may be "
"preferable to adjust or add `conditions <https://spack.readthedocs.io/en/"
"latest/packaging_guide.html#conditional-variants>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:278
msgid ""
"**Action.** Consider asking why the variant (or build option) is being "
"removed and suggest making it conditional when it is still relevant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:283
msgid ""
"If the default value of a variant is changed in the PR, then there is a risk "
"that other packages relying on that value will no longer build as others "
"expect. This may be worth noting in the review."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:289
msgid "``depends_on`` directives"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:291
msgid ""
":ref:`Dependencies <dependencies>` represent software that must be installed "
"before the package builds or is able to work correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:294
msgid "Updating dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:296
msgid ""
"It is important that dependencies reflect the requirements of listed "
"versions. They only need to be checked in a review when versions are being "
"added or removed or the dependencies are being changed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:299
msgid ""
"**Action.** Dependencies affected by such changes should be confirmed, when "
"possible, and *at least* when the Contributor is not a Maintainer of the "
"package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:302
msgid ""
"**Solutions.** In some cases, the needed change may be as simple as ensuring "
"the version ranges (see :ref:`version_compatibility`) and/or variant options "
"in the dependency are accurate. In others, one or more of the dependencies "
"needed by new versions are missing and need to be added. Or there may be "
"dependencies that are no longer relevant when versions requiring them are "
"removed, meaning the dependencies should be removed as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:307
msgid ""
"For example, it is not uncommon for Python package dependencies to be out of "
"date when new versions are added. In this case, check Python package "
"dependencies by following the build system `guidelines <https://spack."
"readthedocs.io/en/latest/build_systems/pythonpackage.html#dependencies>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:312
msgid ""
"In general, refer to the relevant dependencies section, if any, for the "
"package’s :ref:`build-systems` for guidance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:315
msgid "Updating language and compiler dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:317
msgid ""
"When :ref:`language and compiler dependencies <language-dependencies>` were "
"introduced, their ``depends_on`` directives were derived from the source for "
"existing packages. These dependencies are flagged with ``# generated`` "
"comments when they have not been confirmed. Unfortunately, the generated "
"dependencies are not always complete or necessarily required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:321
msgid ""
"**Action.** If these dependencies are being updated, ask that the ``# "
"generated`` comments be removed if the Contributor can confirm they are "
"relevant. Definitely make sure Contributors do **not** include ``# "
"generated`` on the dependencies they are adding to the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:328
msgid "Failed automated checks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:330
msgid ""
"All PRs are expected to pass **at least the required** automated checks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:333
msgid "Style failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:335
msgid "The PR may fail one or more style checks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:337
msgid ""
"**Action.** If the failure is due to issues raised by the ``black`` style "
"checker *and* the PR is otherwise ready to be merged, you can add "
"``@spackbot fix style`` in a comment to see if Spack will fix the errors. "
"Otherwise, inform the Contributor that the style failures need to be "
"addressed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:342
msgid "CI stack failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:344
msgid ""
"Existing packages **may** be included in GitLab CI pipelines through "
"inclusion in one or more `stacks <https://github.com/spack/spack-packages/"
"tree/develop/stacks>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:346
msgid ""
"**Action.** It is worth checking **at least a sampling** of the failed job "
"logs, if present, to determine the possible cause and take or suggest an "
"action accordingly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:349
msgid "**CI Runner Failures**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:350
msgid "Sometimes CI runners time out or the pods become unavailable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:352
msgid ""
"**Action.** If that is the case, the resolution may be as simple as "
"restarting the pipeline by adding a ``@spackbot run pipeline`` comment. "
"Otherwise, the Contributor will need to investigate and resolve the problem."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:356
msgid "**Stand-alone Test Failures**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:357
msgid ""
"Sometimes :ref:`stand-alone tests <cmd-spack-test>` could be causing the "
"build job to time out. If the tests take too long, the issue could be that "
"the package is running too many and/or long running tests. Or the tests may "
"be trying to use resources (e.g., a batch scheduler) that are not available "
"on runners."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:361
msgid ""
"**Action.** If the tests for a package are hanging, at a minimum create a "
"`new issue <https://github.com/spack/spack-packages/issues>`_ if there is "
"not one already, to flag the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:364
msgid ""
"**(Temporary) Solution.** Look at the package implementation to see if the "
"tests are using a batch scheduler or there appear to be too many or long "
"running tests. If that is the case, then a pull request should be created in "
"the ``spack/spack-packages`` repository that adds the package to the "
"``broken-tests-packages`` list in the `ci configuration <https://spack."
"readthedocs.io/en/latest/pipelines.html#ci-yaml>`_. Once the fix PR is "
"merged, then the affected PR can be rebased to pick up the change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:372
msgid "Successful builds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:374
msgid ""
"Is there evidence that the package builds successfully on at least one "
"platform? For a new package, we would ideally have confirmation for every "
"version; whereas, we would want confirmation of only the affected versions "
"for changes to an existing package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:377
msgid "Acceptable forms of confirmation are **one or more of**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:379
msgid ""
"the Contributor or another reviewer explicitly confirms that a successful "
"build of **each new version on at least one platform**;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:380
msgid ""
"the software is built successfully by Spack CI by **at least one of the CI "
"stacks**; and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:381
msgid ""
"**at least one Maintainer** explicitly confirms they are able to "
"successfully build the software."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:383
msgid ""
"Individuals are expected to update the PR description or add a comment to "
"explicitly confirm the builds. You may need to check the CI stacks and/or "
"outputs to confirm that there is a stack that builds the new version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_review_guide.rst:388
msgid ""
"When builds are confirmed by individuals, we would prefer the output of "
"``spack debug report`` be included in either the PR description or a comment."
msgstr ""
